Here's an example of a Laravel middleware that blocks users whose IP is not in an array:

```php
namespace App\Http\Middleware;

use Closure;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;

class IpCheck
{
    public function handle($request, Closure $next)
    {
        $allowedIps = ['192.168.1.1', '192.168.1.2'];

        if (in_array($request->ip(), $allowedIps)) {
            return $next($request);
        }

        abort(403, 'You are not authorized to access this resource.');
    }
}
```

In this example, the `IpCheck` middleware checks if the user's IP is in an array of allowed IPs. If the IP is not in the array, the middleware aborts with a 403 Forbidden status code and a custom error message.

To use this middleware, you can add it to the `$routeMiddleware` array in your `app/Providers/RouteServiceProvider.php` file:

```php
use App\Http\Middleware\IpCheck;

class RouteServiceProvider extends \Illuminate\Routing\Router
{
    protected $middlewareGroups = [
        'web' => [
            \App\Http\Middleware\IpCheck::class,
            \App\Http\Middleware\CheckUserType::class,
        ],
        'api' => [
            'throttle:60,1000',
        ],
    ];

    // ...

}
```

This will ensure that the `IpCheck` middleware is applied to all requests that are part of the `web` middleware group.

