```

JavaScript:

```
// Get the user name from the input field
const userName = document.getElementById("user_name").value;

// Make an API call to add the new user
const apiUrl = "http://localhost:5000/api/users/" + userName + "/devices/d2db5ec4-6e7a-11ee-b962-0242ac120002";

fetch(apiUrl, {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json"
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    "user_name": userName,
    "user_key": "d2db5ec4-6e7a-11ee-b962-0242ac120002",
    "permissions": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Read",
        "description": "Allows the user to read data from the device."
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "name": "Write",
        "description": "Allows the user to write data to the device."
      }
    ]
  })
})
.then(response => response.json())
.then(data => console.log(data))
.catch(error => console.log(error));
```

This code will get the user name from the input field, make an API call to add the new user, and log the response to the console. If there is an error, it will log the error to the console.

To get the deep down nested SVG object Bounding Box using JavaScript, you can use the `getBoundingClientRect()` method. This method returns a `DOMRect` object that represents the size and position of the element relative to the viewport. To get the Bounding Box of a nested SVG object, you can use the `getBoundingClientRect()` method on the nested SVG object. Here's an example:

```javascript
// Get the nested SVG object
const nestedSvg = document.querySelector('#nested-svg');

// Get the Bounding Box of the nested SVG object
const boundingBox = nestedSvg.getBoundingClientRect();

